FC Lorient midfielder, Innocent Bonke, has been drafted as a late replacement for injured Wilfred Ndidi on the Super Eagles squad to face Ghana in crucial World Cup playoffs. After suffering a knee injury in action for Premier League club Leicester City, Ndidi was ruled out of the playoffs by officials. Ndidi, 25, who was in Leicester’s starting eleven against Rennes, had to go off in the 60th minute after sustaining the injury. Below are 7 things to know about Bonke, Ndidi’s replacement for the 2022 World Cup qualifying playoffs between Nigeria and Ghana: Ø On 2 August 2017, Malmö FF announced the signing of Innocent on a contract until 2021 for a fee of €800,000.   Top five most followed football clubs     1994 Eagles triumph at Tinubu’s 70th novelty match     Venezuelan Rojas smashes triple jump world record   Ø Bonke was released by Malmö FF at the end of 2021 and he then signed a 3.5-year contract for Ligue 1 side FC Lorient. Ø Since his move from Malmo FF, Bonke has featured in seven Ligue 1 matches for Christophe Pelissier’s men. Ø He was in action from start to finish as the Merlucciidaes played out a 0-0 home draw with Strasbourg in Sunday’s league outing at the Stade du Moustoir. Ø Super Eagles head coach, Austin Eguavoen, on Sunday, March 20 via the Super Eagles Twitter handle, announced the Lorient midfielder as the man to replace the Leicester player. Ø Bonke, 26, made his debut for the Super Eagles on September 7, 2021 in a World Cup qualifier against Cape Verde, which ended a 2–1 in favour of the Eagles. Ø He also featured in the reversed fixture played at the Teslim Balogun Stadium.